WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:05.500 align:middle line:90%


00:00:05.500 --> 00:00:09.000 align:middle line:90%
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:00:09.000 --> 00:00:16.000 align:middle line:90%


00:00:16.000 --> 00:00:19.260 align:middle line:10%
>>LISA GARR: Hi, Lisa Garr,
host of Gaiam Inspirations.

00:00:19.260 --> 00:00:21.720 align:middle line:10%
Is there a pain that you would
like to heal in your life?

00:00:21.720 --> 00:00:23.276 align:middle line:10%
It could be physical pain.

00:00:23.276 --> 00:00:24.400 align:middle line:90%
It could be emotional pain.

00:00:24.400 --> 00:00:26.940 align:middle line:84%
It could be financial
pain-- any type of pain.

00:00:26.940 --> 00:00:28.410 align:middle line:84%
Well, there's a
technique, which is

00:00:28.410 --> 00:00:31.500 align:middle line:84%
a combination of ancient
Chinese acupressure

00:00:31.500 --> 00:00:34.450 align:middle line:84%
and modern psychology, and it's
called the emotional freedom

00:00:34.450 --> 00:00:35.250 align:middle line:90%
technique.

00:00:35.250 --> 00:00:37.140 align:middle line:90%
It's also known as tapping.

00:00:37.140 --> 00:00:40.817 align:middle line:84%
And it is shown to
significantly alleviate pain.

00:00:40.817 --> 00:00:42.150 align:middle line:90%
Well, joining me is Nick Ortner.

00:00:42.150 --> 00:00:44.340 align:middle line:84%
He is one of the
foremost experts

00:00:44.340 --> 00:00:46.170 align:middle line:84%
on the emotional
freedom technique,

00:00:46.170 --> 00:00:48.540 align:middle line:84%
and he is responsible for
bringing this technique

00:00:48.540 --> 00:00:49.710 align:middle line:90%
to the masses.

00:00:49.710 --> 00:00:50.610 align:middle line:90%
Welcome.

00:00:50.610 --> 00:00:51.300 align:middle line:90%
>>NICK ORTNER: Thank you, Lisa.

00:00:51.300 --> 00:00:51.630 align:middle line:90%
Thank you.

00:00:51.630 --> 00:00:53.080 align:middle line:84%
It's so great to be
here with you today.

00:00:53.080 --> 00:00:54.579 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: It's great
to have you here.

00:00:54.579 --> 00:00:58.030 align:middle line:84%
And you really have done so much
to bring this technique out.

00:00:58.030 --> 00:00:59.250 align:middle line:90%
I don't know how long--

00:00:59.250 --> 00:01:01.080 align:middle line:84%
>>NICK: I'm one of the people
responsible for bringing it

00:01:01.080 --> 00:01:01.880 align:middle line:90%
to the masses.

00:01:01.880 --> 00:01:03.510 align:middle line:84%
There's a lot of
people, but thank you.

00:01:03.510 --> 00:01:05.760 align:middle line:10%
>>LISA: Well, I know you.

00:01:05.760 --> 00:01:10.690 align:middle line:84%
How long ago was EFT, or this
whole concept, brought about?

00:01:10.690 --> 00:01:12.270 align:middle line:84%
>>NICK: It was
actually 30 years ago.

00:01:12.270 --> 00:01:14.020 align:middle line:10%
It's been that long
that it was originally

00:01:14.020 --> 00:01:16.530 align:middle line:10%
discovered, this tapping
process, where we're

00:01:16.530 --> 00:01:19.722 align:middle line:10%
tapping on endpoints of
meridians on our body by a guy

00:01:19.722 --> 00:01:21.390 align:middle line:10%
by the name of Roger Callahan.

00:01:21.390 --> 00:01:23.160 align:middle line:10%
He was a traditional
psychologist

00:01:23.160 --> 00:01:25.370 align:middle line:10%
working with a client,
struggling with a client, who

00:01:25.370 --> 00:01:29.250 align:middle line:10%
had a water phobia, by name of
Mary, and nothing was working.

00:01:29.250 --> 00:01:31.600 align:middle line:10%
They were talking--
traditional talk therapy,

00:01:31.600 --> 00:01:32.580 align:middle line:10%
looking at the water--

00:01:32.580 --> 00:01:33.494 align:middle line:10%
nothing was working.

00:01:33.494 --> 00:01:35.160 align:middle line:10%
And when they were
looking at the water,

00:01:35.160 --> 00:01:37.260 align:middle line:10%
she says-- this was after a
year and a half of working

00:01:37.260 --> 00:01:39.468 align:middle line:10%
on it-- she says, you know,
when I look at that pool,

00:01:39.468 --> 00:01:42.180 align:middle line:10%
I get a queasy feeling
in the pit of my stomach.

00:01:42.180 --> 00:01:43.710 align:middle line:10%
It so happens, the
night before, he

00:01:43.710 --> 00:01:45.720 align:middle line:10%
was reading about the
meridians in the body

00:01:45.720 --> 00:01:48.210 align:middle line:10%
and where they ended, and
that the stomach meridian ends

00:01:48.210 --> 00:01:49.410 align:middle line:10%
underneath the eye.

00:01:49.410 --> 00:01:51.520 align:middle line:10%
So on a whim, he said,
try typing there.

00:01:51.520 --> 00:01:54.840 align:middle line:84%
So Mary taps there and the
phobia clears like that.

00:01:54.840 --> 00:01:55.830 align:middle line:90%
So he was--

00:01:55.830 --> 00:01:57.470 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: So he wasn't an
acupuncturist or anything, he--

00:01:57.470 --> 00:01:59.640 align:middle line:84%
>>NICK: No, he was a
psychologist who was just

00:01:59.640 --> 00:02:01.160 align:middle line:90%
looking at Eastern practices.

00:02:01.160 --> 00:02:05.200 align:middle line:84%
And with that one case, said,
wow, what happened here?

00:02:05.200 --> 00:02:06.452 align:middle line:90%
So he started going deeper.

00:02:06.452 --> 00:02:08.160 align:middle line:84%
You can imagine if
you've been practicing

00:02:08.160 --> 00:02:11.220 align:middle line:84%
traditional psychology for a
decade, two decades, and all

00:02:11.220 --> 00:02:13.650 align:middle line:84%
of a sudden, doing this,
and a water phobia clears,

00:02:13.650 --> 00:02:14.880 align:middle line:90%
you've got to look further.

00:02:14.880 --> 00:02:17.760 align:middle line:84%
He developed a set of
algorithms or a sequence

00:02:17.760 --> 00:02:20.240 align:middle line:84%
where you would do different
tapping for different things.

00:02:20.240 --> 00:02:22.260 align:middle line:10%
So if you were angry,
you would do one thing.

00:02:22.260 --> 00:02:24.150 align:middle line:84%
If you're anxious,
you would do another.

00:02:24.150 --> 00:02:25.650 align:middle line:84%
It was a little
complicated to try

00:02:25.650 --> 00:02:27.399 align:middle line:90%
to remember what to do when.

00:02:27.399 --> 00:02:29.190 align:middle line:10%
It was kind like you
needed a chart to see.

00:02:29.190 --> 00:02:31.620 align:middle line:10%
And then one of the students
by the name of Gary Craig

00:02:31.620 --> 00:02:33.900 align:middle line:10%
is the guy who developed
EFT, and that's

00:02:33.900 --> 00:02:36.434 align:middle line:10%
the form of tapping I do,
emotional freedom techniques.

00:02:36.434 --> 00:02:37.350 align:middle line:10%
And he made it simple.

00:02:37.350 --> 00:02:40.230 align:middle line:10%
He said, let's just hit all the
major end points of meridians

00:02:40.230 --> 00:02:43.304 align:middle line:10%
every time, no matter what, that
way we can get that down pat,

00:02:43.304 --> 00:02:44.970 align:middle line:10%
and then focus on the
rest of the stuff.

00:02:44.970 --> 00:02:46.140 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: End points
of meridians--

00:02:46.140 --> 00:02:47.220 align:middle line:84%
I've never heard
it that way before.

00:02:47.220 --> 00:02:47.820 align:middle line:90%
This is great.

00:02:47.820 --> 00:02:50.220 align:middle line:84%
We're going to go through the
whole history of tapping today.

00:02:50.220 --> 00:02:51.690 align:middle line:84%
So how did you find
it in your life?

00:02:51.690 --> 00:02:52.460 align:middle line:90%
How did it help you?

00:02:52.460 --> 00:02:53.200 align:middle line:90%
>>NICK: Yeah, great question.

00:02:53.200 --> 00:02:53.530 align:middle line:90%
[INTERPOSING VOICES]

00:02:53.530 --> 00:02:55.710 align:middle line:10%
>>NICK: You know,
probably about a decade

00:02:55.710 --> 00:02:57.960 align:middle line:10%
ago now, maybe a
little longer, I

00:02:57.960 --> 00:02:59.765 align:middle line:10%
was just online
and, you know, how

00:02:59.765 --> 00:03:02.355 align:middle line:10%
you follow one link to
another and read about all

00:03:02.355 --> 00:03:03.480 align:middle line:10%
these different techniques.

00:03:03.480 --> 00:03:06.120 align:middle line:10%
I had always been into what
could I do for my own life

00:03:06.120 --> 00:03:07.407 align:middle line:10%
to make it better?

00:03:07.407 --> 00:03:09.240 align:middle line:10%
And I kept reading about
this tapping thing.

00:03:09.240 --> 00:03:10.530 align:middle line:10%
And I was skeptical at first.

00:03:10.530 --> 00:03:13.650 align:middle line:10%
It's like, why are
we hitting ourselves?

00:03:13.650 --> 00:03:15.150 align:middle line:10%
What's happening here?

00:03:15.150 --> 00:03:17.309 align:middle line:10%
but I kept hearing
story after story

00:03:17.309 --> 00:03:19.350 align:middle line:10%
and everywhere I turn
someone else would say, oh,

00:03:19.350 --> 00:03:20.308 align:middle line:10%
have you tried tapping?

00:03:20.308 --> 00:03:22.560 align:middle line:10%
And I said, all right, I'm
going to give it a shot.

00:03:22.560 --> 00:03:24.870 align:middle line:10%
And one of my first
experiences, I remember,

00:03:24.870 --> 00:03:27.480 align:middle line:10%
I had woken up one
morning with neck pain,

00:03:27.480 --> 00:03:29.530 align:middle line:10%
like you get a
crick in your neck.

00:03:29.530 --> 00:03:31.110 align:middle line:10%
It's not the worst,
but it hurts.

00:03:31.110 --> 00:03:32.730 align:middle line:10%
You're kind of like
a robot all day,

00:03:32.730 --> 00:03:34.022 align:middle line:10%
cause you can't turn your head.

00:03:34.022 --> 00:03:35.146 align:middle line:10%
>>LISA: Slept wrong-- yeah.

00:03:35.146 --> 00:03:36.100 align:middle line:10%
>>NICK: Exactly.

00:03:36.100 --> 00:03:38.260 align:middle line:10%
And usually, it takes
a day, two days,

00:03:38.260 --> 00:03:40.290 align:middle line:10%
sometimes three days
for it to clear.

00:03:40.290 --> 00:03:43.020 align:middle line:10%
So I said, you know, I keep
hearing that this tapping thing

00:03:43.020 --> 00:03:44.130 align:middle line:10%
works for pain.

00:03:44.130 --> 00:03:45.080 align:middle line:10%
Let me try it.

00:03:45.080 --> 00:03:46.890 align:middle line:10%
So I pull up the
computer screen,

00:03:46.890 --> 00:03:48.630 align:middle line:10%
follow the instructions.

00:03:48.630 --> 00:03:50.430 align:middle line:84%
I made sure to close
my blinds to make sure

00:03:50.430 --> 00:03:52.280 align:middle line:90%
nobody was watching me--

00:03:52.280 --> 00:03:54.540 align:middle line:84%
the neighbors didn't
think I had lost it.

00:03:54.540 --> 00:03:56.290 align:middle line:84%
And I'm going
through the points,

00:03:56.290 --> 00:03:59.010 align:middle line:84%
going, OK, tapping-- this
pain-- focusing on it.

00:03:59.010 --> 00:04:01.650 align:middle line:84%
And next thing I knew it was
just like where did it go?

00:04:01.650 --> 00:04:02.470 align:middle line:90%
It's gone.

00:04:02.470 --> 00:04:03.270 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: That fast?

00:04:03.270 --> 00:04:04.350 align:middle line:90%
>>NICK: Five or 10 minutes--

00:04:04.350 --> 00:04:04.910 align:middle line:90%
max.

00:04:04.910 --> 00:04:05.330 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Really?

00:04:05.330 --> 00:04:06.538 align:middle line:90%
>>NICK: It cleared that fast.

00:04:06.538 --> 00:04:10.180 align:middle line:84%
And I've seen that happen
so often with pain.

00:04:10.180 --> 00:04:12.340 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: You hear
it all the time.

00:04:12.340 --> 00:04:14.520 align:middle line:84%
So then, how did that
carry on to something

00:04:14.520 --> 00:04:17.690 align:middle line:84%
that you actually have helped
thousands of people with?

00:04:17.690 --> 00:04:20.190 align:middle line:84%
>>NICK: Yes, so initially,
the first couple of years

00:04:20.190 --> 00:04:22.710 align:middle line:84%
was just using it for
myself, with friends,

00:04:22.710 --> 00:04:24.150 align:middle line:90%
and family members.

00:04:24.150 --> 00:04:26.460 align:middle line:10%
The running joke at
the time was don't

00:04:26.460 --> 00:04:28.530 align:middle line:10%
say anything is
wrong around Nick

00:04:28.530 --> 00:04:30.970 align:middle line:10%
because he'll make
you tap on it.

00:04:30.970 --> 00:04:33.600 align:middle line:84%
And you know me, Lisa, and
I'm a little better now.

00:04:33.600 --> 00:04:37.010 align:middle line:84%
Now, I let people come to
me when they want to tap.

00:04:37.010 --> 00:04:39.090 align:middle line:84%
But I was just so excited
about the technique.

00:04:39.090 --> 00:04:41.610 align:middle line:10%
It was so easy to
implement, so easy to share

00:04:41.610 --> 00:04:44.070 align:middle line:10%
with people, and something
they could walk away with.

00:04:44.070 --> 00:04:46.785 align:middle line:10%
So it's like, oh, my shoulder
hurts or I'm upset, this, that,

00:04:46.785 --> 00:04:47.070 align:middle line:10%
and the other.

00:04:47.070 --> 00:04:47.870 align:middle line:10%
Let's try it.

00:04:47.870 --> 00:04:49.860 align:middle line:10%
Let's tap on it.

00:04:49.860 --> 00:04:53.160 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Then you think,
oh, let's do a movie.

00:04:53.160 --> 00:04:55.740 align:middle line:84%
>>NICK: Then I did too much
tapping, got a little crazy,

00:04:55.740 --> 00:04:57.030 align:middle line:90%
and decided to make a movie.

00:04:57.030 --> 00:04:58.641 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Did you
tap on the movie?

00:04:58.641 --> 00:05:01.140 align:middle line:10%
>>NICK: You know, it's funny,
because we're in LA right now,

00:05:01.140 --> 00:05:04.800 align:middle line:10%
filming this, and I was
speaking to a group last night,

00:05:04.800 --> 00:05:07.020 align:middle line:10%
and the idea of making
a documentary in LA

00:05:07.020 --> 00:05:10.632 align:middle line:10%
isn't that far fetched, because
everybody is making something.

00:05:10.632 --> 00:05:11.840 align:middle line:90%
There's film everywhere here.

00:05:11.840 --> 00:05:12.700 align:middle line:90%
But I was in Connecticut.

00:05:12.700 --> 00:05:13.970 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Yeah,
you're right in LA.

00:05:13.970 --> 00:05:16.344 align:middle line:84%
>>NICK: And I had no filmmaking
experience, no background

00:05:16.344 --> 00:05:17.790 align:middle line:90%
whatsoever in film.

00:05:17.790 --> 00:05:20.090 align:middle line:10%
I was just so passionate
about the technique.

00:05:20.090 --> 00:05:22.550 align:middle line:10%
And I said, I would
love the medium of film

00:05:22.550 --> 00:05:24.620 align:middle line:10%
to actually show
what's happening,

00:05:24.620 --> 00:05:26.660 align:middle line:10%
to show that these
results are real,

00:05:26.660 --> 00:05:27.950 align:middle line:10%
not just reading about it.

00:05:27.950 --> 00:05:29.116 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: You need to show it.

00:05:29.116 --> 00:05:31.100 align:middle line:84%
I'm going to show you
an example of the movie.

00:05:31.100 --> 00:05:34.160 align:middle line:84%
This is just explains the
concept of the movie called,

00:05:34.160 --> 00:05:36.396 align:middle line:84%
"The Tapping
Solution," take a look.

00:05:36.396 --> 00:05:38.270 align:middle line:10%
>>CHERYL RICHARDSON:
What I often say is, OK,

00:05:38.270 --> 00:05:39.070 align:middle line:10%
you know what?

00:05:39.070 --> 00:05:41.002 align:middle line:10%
I have this little
technique that I think

00:05:41.002 --> 00:05:42.210 align:middle line:10%
might really be helpful here.

00:05:42.210 --> 00:05:43.430 align:middle line:10%
Now, it might seem
a little strange,

00:05:43.430 --> 00:05:45.638 align:middle line:10%
but if you're willing to
play along and work with me,

00:05:45.638 --> 00:05:47.610 align:middle line:10%
let's just give it a try
and see what happens.

00:05:47.610 --> 00:05:49.100 align:middle line:84%
>>CAROL TUTTLE:
It is a tool that

00:05:49.100 --> 00:05:52.906 align:middle line:84%
allows you to release what's
blocking the powers of healing.

00:05:52.906 --> 00:05:55.280 align:middle line:10%
>>RICK WILKES: If there is an
emotional trauma, something

00:05:55.280 --> 00:05:57.169 align:middle line:10%
happens, something
I watch on CNN,

00:05:57.169 --> 00:05:58.960 align:middle line:10%
something that happens
to a friend of mine,

00:05:58.960 --> 00:06:00.530 align:middle line:10%
something that
happens to me, there

00:06:00.530 --> 00:06:03.530 align:middle line:10%
is an energetic
disruption that occurs.

00:06:03.530 --> 00:06:06.260 align:middle line:10%
And what we do is we bring
some soothing to that.

00:06:06.260 --> 00:06:08.030 align:middle line:10%
>>DR. FRED GALLO:
You bring a problem

00:06:08.030 --> 00:06:13.290 align:middle line:10%
to mind, a trauma for example,
and you tap on your body,

00:06:13.290 --> 00:06:14.280 align:middle line:10%
like this.

00:06:14.280 --> 00:06:17.630 align:middle line:10%
>>RICK: We do that while tapping
into a particular emotional

00:06:17.630 --> 00:06:19.860 align:middle line:10%
state, a feeling in the body.

00:06:19.860 --> 00:06:21.534 align:middle line:84%
And by doing that,
we're soothing it.

00:06:21.534 --> 00:06:22.950 align:middle line:10%
>>JOE VITALE: When
I first learned

00:06:22.950 --> 00:06:24.324 align:middle line:10%
that he was talking
about tapping

00:06:24.324 --> 00:06:27.630 align:middle line:10%
on different points on your
body, I think I was skeptical.

00:06:27.630 --> 00:06:28.960 align:middle line:10%
But I was also desperate.

00:06:28.960 --> 00:06:32.660 align:middle line:84%
>>WOMAN: If I can start to
open up and release some

00:06:32.660 --> 00:06:35.360 align:middle line:84%
of these feelings that
I've had in the past

00:06:35.360 --> 00:06:41.990 align:middle line:84%
and clear away some experiences
that are no longer relevant.

00:06:41.990 --> 00:06:44.960 align:middle line:84%
>>WOMAN: There's no
way I can't change.

00:06:44.960 --> 00:06:46.830 align:middle line:90%
I'm just going to get better.

00:06:46.830 --> 00:06:47.630 align:middle line:90%
I have to.

00:06:47.630 --> 00:06:50.240 align:middle line:90%
There's no possible way.

00:06:50.240 --> 00:06:52.180 align:middle line:84%
>>WOMAN: God, I
just have so much

00:06:52.180 --> 00:06:57.284 align:middle line:84%
that I need to work on
to kind of save my life.

00:06:57.284 --> 00:06:59.200 align:middle line:10%
>>BRAD YATES: I think
it was Thomas Edison who

00:06:59.200 --> 00:07:03.440 align:middle line:10%
said, if we did everything we
could, that we are capable of,

00:07:03.440 --> 00:07:05.139 align:middle line:10%
we would literally
astound ourselves.

00:07:05.139 --> 00:07:06.680 align:middle line:10%
>>JACK CANFIELD:
The problem is we've

00:07:06.680 --> 00:07:09.380 align:middle line:10%
been trained out of that
by our conditioning,

00:07:09.380 --> 00:07:11.237 align:middle line:10%
by schools, by television.

00:07:11.237 --> 00:07:13.820 align:middle line:10%
>>BOB PROCTOR: So I think we got
to take a look at who we are,

00:07:13.820 --> 00:07:16.250 align:middle line:10%
and what we've got,
and how we function,

00:07:16.250 --> 00:07:20.390 align:middle line:10%
and then begin to
apply this information

00:07:20.390 --> 00:07:23.610 align:middle line:10%
in a practical manner to
improve the quality of our life,

00:07:23.610 --> 00:07:25.360 align:middle line:10%
because life is
meant to be enjoyed.

