00:16:19.570 --> 00:16:24.165 align:middle line:84%
So tapping just initiates
an electrical current.

00:16:24.165 --> 00:16:26.040 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: So now that
we're seeing a little bit

00:16:26.040 --> 00:16:30.150 align:middle line:84%
about how it works, what is
some of the science behind it?

00:16:30.150 --> 00:16:30.970 align:middle line:90%
How does that work?

00:16:30.970 --> 00:16:31.310 align:middle line:90%
>>NICK: Great question.

00:16:31.310 --> 00:16:33.362 align:middle line:84%
And there's actually
been more recent research

00:16:33.362 --> 00:16:35.820 align:middle line:84%
since the movie was released
that I'm really excited about.

00:16:35.820 --> 00:16:38.100 align:middle line:10%
And what the latest
research is really showing

00:16:38.100 --> 00:16:40.830 align:middle line:10%
is that when we tap on these
end points of meridians

00:16:40.830 --> 00:16:43.230 align:middle line:10%
of our body, we're actually
sending a calming signal

00:16:43.230 --> 00:16:44.660 align:middle line:10%
to the amygdala in the brain.

00:16:44.660 --> 00:16:46.410 align:middle line:84%
And the amygdala, as
a lot of people know,

00:16:46.410 --> 00:16:49.900 align:middle line:84%
is that very ancient fight
or flight response center.

00:16:49.900 --> 00:16:52.590 align:middle line:84%
It's the part that,
historically, the tiger chases

00:16:52.590 --> 00:16:55.137 align:middle line:84%
you, the amygdala fires,
the blood flows away

00:16:55.137 --> 00:16:56.970 align:middle line:84%
from the brain, from
the gut, so we can run.

00:16:56.970 --> 00:16:57.750 align:middle line:90%
We can fight, we can flee.

00:16:57.750 --> 00:16:58.530 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Into the extremities--

00:16:58.530 --> 00:16:59.330 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:16:59.330 --> 00:17:00.144 align:middle line:90%
>>NICK: Exactly.

00:17:00.144 --> 00:17:01.560 align:middle line:10%
One of the challenges
that we face

00:17:01.560 --> 00:17:03.780 align:middle line:10%
in this very modern,
fast-paced life,

00:17:03.780 --> 00:17:05.760 align:middle line:10%
is that, that amygdala,
that stress response,

00:17:05.760 --> 00:17:07.079 align:middle line:10%
is firing all the time.

00:17:07.079 --> 00:17:09.594 align:middle line:84%
And so, you get an email
from your boss at work

00:17:09.594 --> 00:17:11.010 align:middle line:84%
and you're sitting
at the computer

00:17:11.010 --> 00:17:13.440 align:middle line:84%
and it stresses you
out and there's no

00:17:13.440 --> 00:17:15.339 align:middle line:90%
running or fighting or fleeing.

00:17:15.339 --> 00:17:17.094 align:middle line:10%
That amygdala is
firing, the chemicals

00:17:17.094 --> 00:17:19.260 align:middle line:10%
are coursing through the
body, cortisol is going up,

00:17:19.260 --> 00:17:22.953 align:middle line:10%
adrenaline is going up, and we
don't have a way to release it.

00:17:22.953 --> 00:17:25.619 align:middle line:10%
In fact, if we have these stress
responses and we went for a run

00:17:25.619 --> 00:17:27.810 align:middle line:10%
afterwards-- if we
sprinted right afterwards,

00:17:27.810 --> 00:17:30.070 align:middle line:10%
that would be a
good healthy thing,

00:17:30.070 --> 00:17:33.132 align:middle line:10%
because that's what our
body would naturally do.

00:17:33.132 --> 00:17:34.590 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: To drain
the chemicals out.

00:17:34.590 --> 00:17:35.940 align:middle line:84%
>>NICK: To drain the
chemicals, to actually use

00:17:35.940 --> 00:17:38.530 align:middle line:84%
that energy that feels--
that's why people who exercise,

00:17:38.530 --> 00:17:40.650 align:middle line:84%
go for a run, they find
it to be a massive stress

00:17:40.650 --> 00:17:42.390 align:middle line:90%
reliever, for a good reason.

00:17:42.390 --> 00:17:43.814 align:middle line:10%
>>LISA: Yes, absolutely.

00:17:43.814 --> 00:17:46.480 align:middle line:10%
>>NICK: And what it's also doing
when we're tapping on these end

00:17:46.480 --> 00:17:48.600 align:middle line:10%
points and meridians,
bringing up the stress

00:17:48.600 --> 00:17:50.640 align:middle line:10%
response, whether it
be a current stressor

00:17:50.640 --> 00:17:54.150 align:middle line:10%
or an old stress, an old trauma,
an old issue that's going on,

00:17:54.150 --> 00:17:55.950 align:middle line:10%
we're actually
retraining the brain,

00:17:55.950 --> 00:17:57.460 align:middle line:10%
retraining the memory of it.

00:17:57.460 --> 00:18:00.360 align:middle line:10%
And that's why we can do it
with veterans with PTSD who

00:18:00.360 --> 00:18:02.969 align:middle line:10%
have memories that when
they think about it,

00:18:02.969 --> 00:18:04.510 align:middle line:10%
it's not even safe
to think about it.

00:18:04.510 --> 00:18:05.468 align:middle line:90%
Their body clenches up.

00:18:05.468 --> 00:18:06.630 align:middle line:90%
There's so much pain.

00:18:06.630 --> 00:18:08.700 align:middle line:84%
We can retrain that
memory, retrain

00:18:08.700 --> 00:18:11.190 align:middle line:84%
how it's stored in the body,
so people can think about it

00:18:11.190 --> 00:18:13.680 align:middle line:84%
and go, wow, there's
nothing there.

00:18:13.680 --> 00:18:16.470 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: I was in an car
accident a little while ago

00:18:16.470 --> 00:18:19.920 align:middle line:84%
and I noticed that I was
sitting at the same light

00:18:19.920 --> 00:18:22.170 align:middle line:90%
that I was rear ended at.

00:18:22.170 --> 00:18:23.580 align:middle line:90%
And there was a--

00:18:23.580 --> 00:18:26.100 align:middle line:84%
I rolled my windows down--
this was several months later--

00:18:26.100 --> 00:18:29.430 align:middle line:84%
a gust of wind came and it
shook the car and my whole body

00:18:29.430 --> 00:18:32.560 align:middle line:84%
went immediately into
the accident response.

00:18:32.560 --> 00:18:34.920 align:middle line:10%
>>NICK: And that's a conditioned
response in your body.

00:18:34.920 --> 00:18:38.034 align:middle line:10%
Now that's at a great specific
one that we can notice--

00:18:38.034 --> 00:18:39.450 align:middle line:10%
same thing with
phobias and fears.

00:18:39.450 --> 00:18:40.890 align:middle line:84%
If someone has a
real phobia, they

00:18:40.890 --> 00:18:42.540 align:middle line:84%
notice that
conditioned response.

00:18:42.540 --> 00:18:44.700 align:middle line:10%
But the reality is that,
that conditioned response

00:18:44.700 --> 00:18:47.330 align:middle line:10%
is active in virtually
every part of our lives.

00:18:47.330 --> 00:18:49.740 align:middle line:10%
So when it comes to
weight loss and food,

00:18:49.740 --> 00:18:51.390 align:middle line:10%
that conditioned
responses in place.

00:18:51.390 --> 00:18:52.800 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: How does
that work there?

00:18:52.800 --> 00:18:54.870 align:middle line:90%
>>NICK: Well it's the traumas.

00:18:54.870 --> 00:18:56.910 align:middle line:84%
It's oftentimes the
traumas that we've

00:18:56.910 --> 00:18:58.830 align:middle line:90%
experienced as we grow up.

00:18:58.830 --> 00:19:02.010 align:middle line:84%
So let's say-- and everybody's
story is different, but--

00:19:02.010 --> 00:19:04.470 align:middle line:84%
I've heard things like
someone was 15 years old

00:19:04.470 --> 00:19:05.940 align:middle line:84%
and they were
skinny and in shape

00:19:05.940 --> 00:19:08.070 align:middle line:84%
and looking great and
their older sister said,

00:19:08.070 --> 00:19:10.890 align:middle line:84%
who do you think you
are looking so hot?

00:19:10.890 --> 00:19:13.020 align:middle line:84%
And now it was like,
oh, right there--

00:19:13.020 --> 00:19:16.060 align:middle line:84%
body stores it's not
safe to look like this.

00:19:16.060 --> 00:19:19.140 align:middle line:84%
So now that conditioned response
is running all the time.

00:19:19.140 --> 00:19:20.700 align:middle line:10%
Any time you start
losing weight,

00:19:20.700 --> 00:19:23.615 align:middle line:10%
often not a conscious thing,
oh, something doesn't feel good.

00:19:23.615 --> 00:19:24.490 align:middle line:90%
It doesn't feel safe.

00:19:24.490 --> 00:19:25.406 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: It's not safe.

00:19:25.406 --> 00:19:28.350 align:middle line:84%
>>NICK: Same thing with finances
and standing out in the world.

00:19:28.350 --> 00:19:30.990 align:middle line:10%
The conditioned response--
why is it that so many of us

00:19:30.990 --> 00:19:34.550 align:middle line:10%
go only so far and then
we just hit a wall and go,

00:19:34.550 --> 00:19:36.310 align:middle line:10%
uh-uh, I'm not doing this.

00:19:36.310 --> 00:19:37.110 align:middle line:90%
Why is it that--

00:19:37.110 --> 00:19:39.510 align:middle line:90%
we talk about self sabotage.

00:19:39.510 --> 00:19:40.870 align:middle line:90%
We have a New Year's resolution.

00:19:40.870 --> 00:19:42.750 align:middle line:84%
We have something we
want to make happen,

00:19:42.750 --> 00:19:44.430 align:middle line:84%
and we make a little
bit of progress,

00:19:44.430 --> 00:19:46.600 align:middle line:84%
and then go, no,
I'm not doing it.

00:19:46.600 --> 00:19:49.085 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: So can you
really tap around say,

00:19:49.085 --> 00:19:51.210 align:middle line:84%
a New Year's resolution
to keep it active?

00:19:51.210 --> 00:19:52.800 align:middle line:84%
>>NICK: Yeah, you
can, absolutely.

00:19:52.800 --> 00:19:54.210 align:middle line:90%
It's a great time to do it.

00:19:54.210 --> 00:19:57.290 align:middle line:84%
And I was-- defined because
you talked about the questions

00:19:57.290 --> 00:19:58.090 align:middle line:90%
before, right?

00:19:58.090 --> 00:19:58.322 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Yes.

00:19:58.322 --> 00:19:59.310 align:middle line:84%
>>NICK: It's really
about the questions

00:19:59.310 --> 00:20:00.720 align:middle line:90%
that we ask ourselves.

00:20:00.720 --> 00:20:03.849 align:middle line:84%
And of the ways to do it on
our own is to say, OK, here's

00:20:03.849 --> 00:20:04.890 align:middle line:90%
my New Year's resolution.

00:20:04.890 --> 00:20:07.650 align:middle line:84%
Let's say it's to
lose 30 pounds.

00:20:07.650 --> 00:20:09.870 align:middle line:84%
So you write it down,
whatever you normally do.

00:20:09.870 --> 00:20:13.267 align:middle line:84%
Now, the next step is to
imagine it actually happening.

00:20:13.267 --> 00:20:15.600 align:middle line:84%
So you close your eyes, you
have a little visualization,

00:20:15.600 --> 00:20:17.970 align:middle line:84%
and you say, OK,
let's say in June,

00:20:17.970 --> 00:20:20.090 align:middle line:84%
I've actually lost
the 30 pounds.

00:20:20.090 --> 00:20:21.840 align:middle line:84%
And really pay attention
to what comes up.

00:20:21.840 --> 00:20:24.125 align:middle line:84%
Now, there'll be some good
feelings, like, oh, wow,

00:20:24.125 --> 00:20:24.925 align:middle line:90%
I did this.

00:20:24.925 --> 00:20:25.960 align:middle line:90%
This is great.

00:20:25.960 --> 00:20:27.840 align:middle line:84%
And then if you pay
close attention,

00:20:27.840 --> 00:20:29.320 align:middle line:84%
there'll be some
negative feelings.

00:20:29.320 --> 00:20:30.000 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Look for those.

00:20:30.000 --> 00:20:30.958 align:middle line:90%
>>NICK: Look for those.

00:20:30.958 --> 00:20:32.010 align:middle line:90%
There'll be things like--

00:20:32.010 --> 00:20:34.385 align:middle line:84%
one of things that you can do
is have your family members

00:20:34.385 --> 00:20:35.940 align:middle line:84%
and your friends
walk in the room

00:20:35.940 --> 00:20:39.050 align:middle line:84%
when you're running that
visualization, not in person,

00:20:39.050 --> 00:20:39.850 align:middle line:90%
in that vision.

00:20:39.850 --> 00:20:43.800 align:middle line:10%
So you see yourself 30 pounds
lighter in your bathing suit

00:20:43.800 --> 00:20:46.532 align:middle line:10%
and now you see all these people
you love walking into the room.

00:20:46.532 --> 00:20:47.573 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: What do they say?

00:20:47.573 --> 00:20:48.750 align:middle line:90%
>>NICK: How does that feel?

00:20:48.750 --> 00:20:49.590 align:middle line:90%
What do they say?

00:20:49.590 --> 00:20:51.360 align:middle line:90%
What's that interaction like?

00:20:51.360 --> 00:20:53.840 align:middle line:84%
And people will
very quickly go, oh,

00:20:53.840 --> 00:20:55.895 align:middle line:84%
if something doesn't
feel safe about that.

00:20:55.895 --> 00:20:57.690 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: They'll notice
something alarming.

00:20:57.690 --> 00:20:58.490 align:middle line:90%
>>NICK: Exactly.

00:20:58.490 --> 00:21:00.120 align:middle line:90%
And it's that inquiry process.

00:21:00.120 --> 00:21:01.269 align:middle line:90%
Because when we see that--

00:21:01.269 --> 00:21:03.060 align:middle line:84%
not only can we actually
tap on that scene,

00:21:03.060 --> 00:21:05.200 align:middle line:84%
so we can actually
have the visualization,

00:21:05.200 --> 00:21:07.320 align:middle line:84%
and when we feel that
restriction, tap.

00:21:07.320 --> 00:21:10.586 align:middle line:84%
We can also ask ourselves the
questions, when did this start?

00:21:10.586 --> 00:21:11.460 align:middle line:90%
What's going on here?

00:21:11.460 --> 00:21:13.477 align:middle line:84%
Really, what's
underneath this stuff?

00:21:13.477 --> 00:21:15.060 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Does it
usually always go back

00:21:15.060 --> 00:21:18.060 align:middle line:84%
to a childhood memory,
a trauma, something?

00:21:18.060 --> 00:21:20.100 align:middle line:84%
>>NICK: So many of
these things do.

00:21:20.100 --> 00:21:21.609 align:middle line:90%
They really do.

00:21:21.609 --> 00:21:23.400 align:middle line:84%
Not always, sometimes
you'll find something

00:21:23.400 --> 00:21:26.330 align:middle line:84%
happened in your 20s
or 30s and everything

00:21:26.330 --> 00:21:28.104 align:middle line:90%
was going great until then.

00:21:28.104 --> 00:21:30.395 align:middle line:84%
But all too often, and no
matter what the issue is-- we

00:21:30.395 --> 00:21:32.390 align:middle line:84%
could be talking about
finances and weight loss

00:21:32.390 --> 00:21:36.220 align:middle line:84%
and relationships-- it'll
come back to mom and dad.

00:21:36.220 --> 00:21:38.840 align:middle line:84%
It'll come back to the things
that you heard growing up,

00:21:38.840 --> 00:21:41.260 align:middle line:84%
the things that you were told,
things that, oftentimes--

00:21:41.260 --> 00:21:43.760 align:middle line:84%
there's a lot of negative stuff
and a lot of pain and trauma

00:21:43.760 --> 00:21:46.880 align:middle line:84%
and abuse, but there's also
stuff that would seem positive,

00:21:46.880 --> 00:21:48.470 align:middle line:84%
but we interpreted
it the wrong way

00:21:48.470 --> 00:21:49.760 align:middle line:90%
or we felt too much pressure.

00:21:49.760 --> 00:21:51.501 align:middle line:84%
Our parents were
trying to help us out,

00:21:51.501 --> 00:21:53.000 align:middle line:84%
but they put a lot
of pressure on us

00:21:53.000 --> 00:21:55.340 align:middle line:84%
and now we've applied that
pressure to ourselves.

00:21:55.340 --> 00:21:57.150 align:middle line:84%
We can never stop
being a perfectionism.

00:21:57.150 --> 00:21:58.370 align:middle line:90%
We can never slow down.

00:21:58.370 --> 00:22:00.380 align:middle line:84%
We can never deeply
and completely

00:22:00.380 --> 00:22:01.630 align:middle line:90%
love and accept ourselves.

00:22:01.630 --> 00:22:02.430 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Right.

00:22:02.430 --> 00:22:03.370 align:middle line:90%
Well I want to see--

00:22:03.370 --> 00:22:05.920 align:middle line:84%
I want to take a look at
what the tapping points are,

00:22:05.920 --> 00:22:07.628 align:middle line:84%
so you can learn a
little bit about that.

00:22:07.628 --> 00:22:08.847 align:middle line:90%
Take a look.

00:22:08.847 --> 00:22:10.430 align:middle line:84%
>>RICK: So let's go
through the points

00:22:10.430 --> 00:22:12.080 align:middle line:84%
real quickly, so
that you know what

00:22:12.080 --> 00:22:14.390 align:middle line:90%
points we're talking about.

00:22:14.390 --> 00:22:18.420 align:middle line:84%
We start with a
karate chop point.

00:22:18.420 --> 00:22:20.570 align:middle line:90%
It's along the side of the hand.

00:22:20.570 --> 00:22:23.900 align:middle line:84%
And use your fingertips and just
tap on the side of your hand

00:22:23.900 --> 00:22:25.010 align:middle line:90%
like that.

00:22:25.010 --> 00:22:27.830 align:middle line:84%
We will start here and do a
lot of tapping here while we

00:22:27.830 --> 00:22:28.880 align:middle line:90%
make certain statements.

00:22:28.880 --> 00:22:31.310 align:middle line:84%
I'm going to talk
about that in a minute.

00:22:31.310 --> 00:22:34.170 align:middle line:84%
During the dark
moments of your day,

00:22:34.170 --> 00:22:36.620 align:middle line:84%
what might you say about
your immune system?

00:22:36.620 --> 00:22:37.880 align:middle line:90%
>>AUDIENCE: It's failing me.

00:22:37.880 --> 00:22:38.930 align:middle line:90%
>>RICK: It's failing me.

00:22:38.930 --> 00:22:42.530 align:middle line:84%
So what we would say is, even
though my immune system is

00:22:42.530 --> 00:22:48.950 align:middle line:84%
failing me right now, I deeply
and completely accept myself.

00:22:48.950 --> 00:22:51.500 align:middle line:90%
And we state that three times.

00:22:51.500 --> 00:22:54.920 align:middle line:84%
Now, you would then start
tapping on these other points.

00:22:54.920 --> 00:22:57.620 align:middle line:84%
And we use what's called
a reminder phrase.

00:22:57.620 --> 00:23:00.650 align:middle line:84%
My immune system and all
the ways that it fails me--

00:23:00.650 --> 00:23:02.510 align:middle line:84%
I'm just coming up
with something--

00:23:02.510 --> 00:23:05.540 align:middle line:84%
my immune system and all
the ways that it fails me.

00:23:05.540 --> 00:23:09.650 align:middle line:84%
My immune system and all
the ways that it fails me.

00:23:09.650 --> 00:23:13.520 align:middle line:84%
My immune system and all
the ways that it fails me.

00:23:13.520 --> 00:23:15.080 align:middle line:90%
Now when you're tapping--

00:23:15.080 --> 00:23:19.940 align:middle line:84%
if you were to imagine drumming
on a table and making a noise--

00:23:19.940 --> 00:23:22.400 align:middle line:84%
that's about how much
pressure you want to use,

00:23:22.400 --> 00:23:24.980 align:middle line:84%
so that you're really
connecting with the bone

00:23:24.980 --> 00:23:26.760 align:middle line:90%
underneath the tissue.

00:23:26.760 --> 00:23:27.560 align:middle line:90%
You don't have to--

00:23:27.560 --> 00:23:29.540 align:middle line:84%
some people really tap
hard thinking that's

00:23:29.540 --> 00:23:31.490 align:middle line:90%
going to do a big difference.

00:23:31.490 --> 00:23:33.670 align:middle line:84%
It doesn't make that
much difference.

00:23:33.670 --> 00:23:38.120 align:middle line:84%
You know, really intense
tapping, that's not necessary.

00:23:38.120 --> 00:23:39.800 align:middle line:90%
Some people tap in a circle.

00:23:39.800 --> 00:23:42.740 align:middle line:90%
Some people will pat their head.

00:23:42.740 --> 00:23:46.020 align:middle line:84%
You just gently tap
the top of the head.

00:23:46.020 --> 00:23:47.900 align:middle line:10%
Now it's just about the
center of your head.

00:23:47.900 --> 00:23:51.280 align:middle line:90%


00:23:51.280 --> 00:23:56.460 align:middle line:84%
So the eyebrow point is at
the beginning of your eyebrow.

00:23:56.460 --> 00:23:57.750 align:middle line:90%
And it's on both sides.

00:23:57.750 --> 00:24:01.960 align:middle line:84%
So sometimes you can tap
with both hands, one hand.

00:24:01.960 --> 00:24:04.669 align:middle line:84%
You can crossover--
doesn't really matter.

00:24:04.669 --> 00:24:06.960 align:middle line:84%
Sometimes, I feel like I want
a little more stimulation

00:24:06.960 --> 00:24:08.320 align:middle line:90%
and I'll use both hands.

00:24:08.320 --> 00:24:10.290 align:middle line:84%
So the next point is
along the side of the eye.

00:24:10.290 --> 00:24:12.570 align:middle line:84%
Now it's not so close it makes
you blink and not so far back

00:24:12.570 --> 00:24:14.278 align:middle line:84%
that you feel like
you're on your temple.

00:24:14.278 --> 00:24:15.750 align:middle line:84%
It's really on the
bone right here.

00:24:15.750 --> 00:24:16.550 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:24:16.550 --> 00:24:19.220 align:middle line:90%


00:24:19.220 --> 00:24:20.990 align:middle line:90%
Everybody got that?

00:24:20.990 --> 00:24:22.010 align:middle line:90%
Under the eye point--

00:24:22.010 --> 00:24:24.620 align:middle line:84%
it's a little sensitive, so
you don't want to bang on it

00:24:24.620 --> 00:24:25.700 align:middle line:90%
real hard.

00:24:25.700 --> 00:24:28.390 align:middle line:84%
But it's right directly
below the pupil

00:24:28.390 --> 00:24:31.040 align:middle line:90%
and just tap gently there.

00:24:31.040 --> 00:24:32.480 align:middle line:90%
Under the nose.

00:24:32.480 --> 00:24:35.470 align:middle line:84%
Now, I curl my lip down a little
bit when I tap under the nose,

00:24:35.470 --> 00:24:38.180 align:middle line:84%
cause I want to be able to
make it a little firmer.

00:24:38.180 --> 00:24:39.640 align:middle line:90%
It's not necessary.

00:24:39.640 --> 00:24:40.988 align:middle line:90%
You all right?

00:24:40.988 --> 00:24:42.120 align:middle line:90%
It tickled?

00:24:42.120 --> 00:24:42.920 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:24:42.920 --> 00:24:44.870 align:middle line:90%
So try a little firmer--

00:24:44.870 --> 00:24:45.770 align:middle line:90%
a little firmer.

00:24:45.770 --> 00:24:48.920 align:middle line:90%


00:24:48.920 --> 00:24:50.974 align:middle line:84%
Chin-- it's not actually
down on the chin.

00:24:50.974 --> 00:24:52.140 align:middle line:90%
They call it the chin point.

00:24:52.140 --> 00:24:54.480 align:middle line:90%
It's in the crease here.

00:24:54.480 --> 00:24:55.350 align:middle line:90%
And just tap there.

00:24:55.350 --> 00:25:00.590 align:middle line:90%


00:25:00.590 --> 00:25:02.430 align:middle line:90%
Now the collarbone point--

00:25:02.430 --> 00:25:05.730 align:middle line:84%
the collarbone itself--
you have it on both sides.

00:25:05.730 --> 00:25:08.190 align:middle line:84%
It's where the whole shoulder
attaches to your body.

00:25:08.190 --> 00:25:10.740 align:middle line:84%
So find that bone on
both sides, and then come

00:25:10.740 --> 00:25:15.970 align:middle line:84%
down about an inch into the
soft tissue right there.

00:25:15.970 --> 00:25:18.150 align:middle line:90%
These are under the arm points.

00:25:18.150 --> 00:25:20.910 align:middle line:84%
Now the underarm points is
not way up in the armpit

00:25:20.910 --> 00:25:26.510 align:middle line:84%
it's about mid bra line for
women, about hand width.

00:25:26.510 --> 00:25:28.850 align:middle line:84%
If you start feeling very
emotional about anything that

00:25:28.850 --> 00:25:31.520 align:middle line:90%
comes up, just start tapping.

00:25:31.520 --> 00:25:33.450 align:middle line:84%
And then, you're
going to notice--

00:25:33.450 --> 00:25:35.450 align:middle line:84%
every once in a while,
you can stop, take a look

00:25:35.450 --> 00:25:37.920 align:middle line:84%
at where your
intensity is on that,

00:25:37.920 --> 00:25:40.662 align:middle line:90%
and notice that it will shift.

00:25:40.662 --> 00:25:42.245 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: So now that
