One in particular,
Dr. Lori Leyden

00:45:39.600 --> 00:45:43.230 align:middle line:84%
who had been working in Rwanda
for the previous five years

00:45:43.230 --> 00:45:46.436 align:middle line:84%
tapping with genocide
survivors in Rwanda

00:45:46.436 --> 00:45:48.060 align:middle line:84%
with children who
had lost her siblings

00:45:48.060 --> 00:45:49.410 align:middle line:90%
and their parents in Rwanda.

00:45:49.410 --> 00:45:51.090 align:middle line:10%
And it's interesting,
because this

00:45:51.090 --> 00:45:54.660 align:middle line:10%
work that I and the
tapping solution company

00:45:54.660 --> 00:45:57.042 align:middle line:10%
had been supporting the
previous couple of years.

00:45:57.042 --> 00:45:58.750 align:middle line:84%
We were excited about
what she was doing.

00:45:58.750 --> 00:46:02.100 align:middle line:84%
And we raised over
$250,000 for her work.

00:46:02.100 --> 00:46:04.110 align:middle line:84%
And then, when I called
her-- and she was

00:46:04.110 --> 00:46:06.060 align:middle line:84%
in California at the
time-- and I said, look,

00:46:06.060 --> 00:46:07.200 align:middle line:90%
here's what we have.

00:46:07.200 --> 00:46:08.570 align:middle line:90%
I'm in Newtown.

00:46:08.570 --> 00:46:11.340 align:middle line:90%
We've got to do something.

00:46:11.340 --> 00:46:14.160 align:middle line:84%
And she flew in that--
she was there by Tuesday.

00:46:14.160 --> 00:46:16.740 align:middle line:90%
So just a few days afterwards.

00:46:16.740 --> 00:46:19.740 align:middle line:84%
And we established the
Tapping Solution Foundation,

00:46:19.740 --> 00:46:21.180 align:middle line:90%
established volunteers.

00:46:21.180 --> 00:46:22.470 align:middle line:90%
We've had about 40 volunteers.

00:46:22.470 --> 00:46:24.450 align:middle line:84%
We had hundreds of
applications for volunteers.

00:46:24.450 --> 00:46:25.250 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Oh, wow.

00:46:25.250 --> 00:46:26.166 align:middle line:90%
>>NICK: 40 volunteers.

00:46:26.166 --> 00:46:28.440 align:middle line:84%
And shortly, a week
after, we were already

00:46:28.440 --> 00:46:30.570 align:middle line:84%
working with people,
tapping with people--

00:46:30.570 --> 00:46:32.210 align:middle line:84%
with first responders,
with parents

00:46:32.210 --> 00:46:34.501 align:middle line:84%
who had lost their children,
with people in the school,

00:46:34.501 --> 00:46:36.030 align:middle line:90%
with people in the community--

00:46:36.030 --> 00:46:39.330 align:middle line:84%
using this tapping technique
to deal with the stress

00:46:39.330 --> 00:46:42.540 align:middle line:84%
and the trauma of the situation
to try to lighten the load.

00:46:42.540 --> 00:46:45.480 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: So first responders--
let's start with those people.

00:46:45.480 --> 00:46:47.590 align:middle line:84%
Did you get a hold
of the Red Cross

00:46:47.590 --> 00:46:48.840 align:middle line:90%
or the people that were there?

00:46:48.840 --> 00:46:49.320 align:middle line:90%
>>NICK: Yeah.

00:46:49.320 --> 00:46:51.060 align:middle line:84%
Well, we, actually,
from the beginning,

00:46:51.060 --> 00:46:54.490 align:middle line:84%
we were very quiet about
the work we were doing.

00:46:54.490 --> 00:46:56.980 align:middle line:84%
It was a situation unlike
any the world has faced.

00:46:56.980 --> 00:46:57.780 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Ever.

00:46:57.780 --> 00:46:59.405 align:middle line:84%
>>NICK: One of the
things that happened

00:46:59.405 --> 00:47:03.810 align:middle line:84%
was that there was about
100-200-300 organizations who

00:47:03.810 --> 00:47:05.130 align:middle line:90%
all went in to help.

00:47:05.130 --> 00:47:06.750 align:middle line:90%
That was their first response.

00:47:06.750 --> 00:47:09.780 align:middle line:84%
I read somewhere there were
68,000 Teddy bears sent in.

00:47:09.780 --> 00:47:11.840 align:middle line:84%
And so, there was
all this energy.

00:47:11.840 --> 00:47:13.590 align:middle line:84%
And we started slowly
working with people,

00:47:13.590 --> 00:47:17.872 align:middle line:84%
but this is a new technique and
it's just now being accepted.

00:47:17.872 --> 00:47:19.830 align:middle line:84%
There's psychologists
and psychiatrists use it,

00:47:19.830 --> 00:47:22.240 align:middle line:84%
but being extra accepted
by the mainstream.

00:47:22.240 --> 00:47:24.660 align:middle line:84%
And we don't want
to force our way in.

00:47:24.660 --> 00:47:27.030 align:middle line:84%
We knew, and I knew
personally, I live in the town.

00:47:27.030 --> 00:47:28.030 align:middle line:90%
I'm not going anywhere.

00:47:28.030 --> 00:47:29.550 align:middle line:90%
So we're going to be here.

00:47:29.550 --> 00:47:32.460 align:middle line:84%
And what's happened-- we started
working with people right away,

00:47:32.460 --> 00:47:36.270 align:middle line:84%
but it's really been
now 11 months later,

00:47:36.270 --> 00:47:38.970 align:middle line:90%
where people are coming to us.

00:47:38.970 --> 00:47:41.130 align:middle line:84%
Just last weekend,
Lori presented

00:47:41.130 --> 00:47:43.770 align:middle line:84%
in front of 100 Connecticut
counselors, the Connecticut

00:47:43.770 --> 00:47:46.830 align:middle line:84%
Counselors Association, who
said we hear about the results

00:47:46.830 --> 00:47:47.910 align:middle line:90%
that you're getting.

00:47:47.910 --> 00:47:49.207 align:middle line:90%
Teach us what you're doing.

00:47:49.207 --> 00:47:50.040 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Interesting.

00:47:50.040 --> 00:47:52.590 align:middle line:84%
>>NICK: We've
trained over 120, I

00:47:52.590 --> 00:47:54.850 align:middle line:84%
think at this point,
psychologists, counselors,

00:47:54.850 --> 00:47:56.190 align:middle line:90%
therapists in the town.

00:47:56.190 --> 00:47:57.314 align:middle line:90%
Our model is to not--

00:47:57.314 --> 00:47:58.980 align:middle line:84%
we can't handle all
the work ourselves--

00:47:58.980 --> 00:48:00.938 align:middle line:84%
it's to train the people
in the front lines who

00:48:00.938 --> 00:48:02.460 align:middle line:90%
are doing this work.

00:48:02.460 --> 00:48:06.270 align:middle line:84%
And now, we're finding,
because sadly, the existing

00:48:06.270 --> 00:48:08.010 align:middle line:84%
tools that are in
place just don't

00:48:08.010 --> 00:48:10.970 align:middle line:90%
work for this level of trauma.

00:48:10.970 --> 00:48:13.140 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: The tapping is
very effective for PTSD.

00:48:13.140 --> 00:48:16.350 align:middle line:84%
There's a whole study that's
been done about it at Harvard,

00:48:16.350 --> 00:48:17.150 align:middle line:90%
right?

00:48:17.150 --> 00:48:18.090 align:middle line:90%
>>NICK: Yeah.

00:48:18.090 --> 00:48:19.464 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Oh, Dawson
Church did it.

00:48:19.464 --> 00:48:21.210 align:middle line:84%
>>NICK: Yeah, Dawson
Church did it.

00:48:21.210 --> 00:48:24.150 align:middle line:10%
And it's showing very
clearly that it's getting

00:48:24.150 --> 00:48:25.930 align:middle line:10%
to the root of this trauma.

00:48:25.930 --> 00:48:27.460 align:middle line:84%
And that's why
we're being called

00:48:27.460 --> 00:48:30.110 align:middle line:84%
in by the traditional
therapists who are saying, look,

00:48:30.110 --> 00:48:32.410 align:middle line:84%
we've been doing our best,
and well-intentioned,

00:48:32.410 --> 00:48:34.537 align:middle line:84%
we're doing our best, but
nobody is getting better.

00:48:34.537 --> 00:48:36.120 align:middle line:84%
And in fact, people
are getting worse.

00:48:36.120 --> 00:48:37.330 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Wow.

00:48:37.330 --> 00:48:38.590 align:middle line:90%
>>NICK: So we're excited--

00:48:38.590 --> 00:48:40.506 align:middle line:84%
not that people are
getting worse, obviously--

00:48:40.506 --> 00:48:43.750 align:middle line:84%
but that people are recognizing
that the tapping can help.

00:48:43.750 --> 00:48:46.150 align:middle line:90%
So making a lot of progress.

00:48:46.150 --> 00:48:48.090 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: And now how
did you meet Scarlett?

00:48:48.090 --> 00:48:51.430 align:middle line:84%
>>NICK: So Scarlett Lewis,
who has become a dear friend,

00:48:51.430 --> 00:48:55.320 align:middle line:84%
she lost her son, Jesse, in the
shooting-- six-year-old Jesse.

00:48:55.320 --> 00:48:57.040 align:middle line:90%
This brave, brave boy.

00:48:57.040 --> 00:48:59.450 align:middle line:10%
It came out afterwards
that he yelled

00:48:59.450 --> 00:49:02.710 align:middle line:10%
run when Adam Lanza's gun
jammed and saved six kids

00:49:02.710 --> 00:49:04.370 align:middle line:10%
and it's in the police report.

00:49:04.370 --> 00:49:04.910 align:middle line:10%
>>LISA: How did they know that?

00:49:04.910 --> 00:49:06.576 align:middle line:10%
>>NICK: He was he was
in the classroom--

00:49:06.576 --> 00:49:09.310 align:middle line:10%
because the kids
that ran survived

00:49:09.310 --> 00:49:11.980 align:middle line:10%
and said that it
was Jesse who knew,

00:49:11.980 --> 00:49:13.390 align:middle line:10%
at some level,
what was going on.

00:49:13.390 --> 00:49:16.450 align:middle line:84%
You know, Scarlett always
says that he's super smart kid

00:49:16.450 --> 00:49:17.390 align:middle line:90%
and with it and just--

00:49:17.390 --> 00:49:18.190 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Six?

00:49:18.190 --> 00:49:19.420 align:middle line:90%
>>NICK: Six, yeah.

00:49:19.420 --> 00:49:23.860 align:middle line:84%
He knew that-- and he yelled
run when people were frozen.

00:49:23.860 --> 00:49:26.497 align:middle line:84%
And six kids lived
and he didn't make it.

00:49:26.497 --> 00:49:28.330 align:middle line:84%
We were introduced to
Scarlett about a month

00:49:28.330 --> 00:49:31.490 align:middle line:84%
after the shooting
through a mutual friend.

00:49:31.490 --> 00:49:33.850 align:middle line:84%
And again, Scarlett
had been trying

00:49:33.850 --> 00:49:35.950 align:middle line:90%
a lot of different things.

00:49:35.950 --> 00:49:39.190 align:middle line:84%
Well-intentioned people
giving horrible advice often.

00:49:39.190 --> 00:49:42.280 align:middle line:84%
She said she met with
someone and they said,

00:49:42.280 --> 00:49:44.720 align:middle line:90%
I lost my son 14 years ago.

00:49:44.720 --> 00:49:47.660 align:middle line:84%
And she said, oh my
gosh, I'm so sorry.

00:49:47.660 --> 00:49:50.690 align:middle line:84%
And she said, and you will
never feel better again.

00:49:50.690 --> 00:49:54.244 align:middle line:84%
In that moment of tragedy,
in the moment of despair,

00:49:54.244 --> 00:49:55.660 align:middle line:84%
isn't helpful, as
well-intentioned

00:49:55.660 --> 00:49:56.460 align:middle line:90%
as it might be.

00:49:56.460 --> 00:49:59.850 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: So she wrote a
book about her experience.

00:49:59.850 --> 00:50:01.390 align:middle line:90%
What was the story?

00:50:01.390 --> 00:50:07.660 align:middle line:84%
>>NICK: Well, she had incredible
experiences after Jessie died,

00:50:07.660 --> 00:50:09.874 align:middle line:84%
things like finding a
chalkboard in her house.

00:50:09.874 --> 00:50:11.290 align:middle line:84%
She had this big,
long chalkboard,

00:50:11.290 --> 00:50:13.780 align:middle line:84%
which I've seen in person,
and on it scribbled,

00:50:13.780 --> 00:50:17.470 align:middle line:84%
they found weeks later, it
said nurturing, healing, love

00:50:17.470 --> 00:50:21.080 align:middle line:84%
written by Jessie, at
some point, weeks earlier.

00:50:21.080 --> 00:50:23.710 align:middle line:10%
And you see very clearly
it's spelled phonetically.

00:50:23.710 --> 00:50:25.090 align:middle line:90%
It's not spelled right.

00:50:25.090 --> 00:50:26.697 align:middle line:90%
It's in his handwriting.

00:50:26.697 --> 00:50:28.780 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Yeah, let's take
a look at this, actually.

00:50:28.780 --> 00:50:31.150 align:middle line:84%
Take a look at this
trailer here of the book.

00:50:31.150 --> 00:50:34.820 align:middle line:84%
>>MAN: We have so
many reasons to have

00:50:34.820 --> 00:50:39.700 align:middle line:84%
the hearts filled with pain
in the world we live in.

00:50:39.700 --> 00:50:42.440 align:middle line:84%
And there is a woman here
in the audience today

00:50:42.440 --> 00:50:47.930 align:middle line:84%
who is the mother of a
little boy named Jessie

00:50:47.930 --> 00:50:53.300 align:middle line:84%
who was shot down in
Newtown, Connecticut just

00:50:53.300 --> 00:50:56.080 align:middle line:90%
a few months ago.

00:50:56.080 --> 00:50:59.770 align:middle line:84%
She has such an
amazing story to tell

00:50:59.770 --> 00:51:02.110 align:middle line:84%
and has decided that
she is not going

00:51:02.110 --> 00:51:04.540 align:middle line:90%
to have pain in her heart.

00:51:04.540 --> 00:51:06.614 align:middle line:84%
This is Scarlett Lewis,
ladies and gentlemen.

00:51:06.614 --> 00:51:08.590 align:middle line:90%
[APPLAUSE]

00:51:08.590 --> 00:51:10.450 align:middle line:84%
>>SCARLETT LEWIS:
Thank you very much.

00:51:10.450 --> 00:51:13.670 align:middle line:90%
I love talking about Jesse.

00:51:13.670 --> 00:51:16.050 align:middle line:84%
I speak of Jesse in
the present tense,

00:51:16.050 --> 00:51:19.610 align:middle line:84%
because I feel him all
around me, all the time.

00:51:19.610 --> 00:51:23.510 align:middle line:10%
When I was at the
firehouse, that day,

00:51:23.510 --> 00:51:27.380 align:middle line:10%
waiting for my
child to come to me,

00:51:27.380 --> 00:51:29.480 align:middle line:10%
and all the other
children had come and gone

00:51:29.480 --> 00:51:33.170 align:middle line:10%
with their parents, and there
were a few of us waiting,

00:51:33.170 --> 00:51:35.480 align:middle line:10%
we were scared.

00:51:35.480 --> 00:51:38.510 align:middle line:90%
And you kept holding out hope.

00:51:38.510 --> 00:51:42.920 align:middle line:10%
But when I began to
realize what had happened,

00:51:42.920 --> 00:51:50.690 align:middle line:10%
I knew in my heart that Jesse
had done something brave,

00:51:50.690 --> 00:51:59.120 align:middle line:10%
that if he was in spirit, he
had died trying to save someone.

00:51:59.120 --> 00:52:01.820 align:middle line:90%
So I carry this with me.

00:52:01.820 --> 00:52:03.840 align:middle line:84%
And I stayed at my mom's
for a couple of weeks.

00:52:03.840 --> 00:52:07.250 align:middle line:84%
It was too painful
to go to my own house

00:52:07.250 --> 00:52:09.560 align:middle line:90%
with all the memories of Jesse.

00:52:09.560 --> 00:52:12.590 align:middle line:84%
And about two weeks
after I was there,

00:52:12.590 --> 00:52:17.600 align:middle line:84%
I noticed writing on my
chalkboard in my kitchen.

00:52:17.600 --> 00:52:19.670 align:middle line:84%
I don't know when
Jesse had written it,

00:52:19.670 --> 00:52:23.300 align:middle line:84%
but it was shortly
before he died.

00:52:23.300 --> 00:52:27.560 align:middle line:84%
And it says, nurturing,
healing, love.

00:52:27.560 --> 00:52:29.670 align:middle line:90%
So it's phonetically spelled.

00:52:29.670 --> 00:52:30.470 align:middle line:90%
[LAUGHING]

00:52:30.470 --> 00:52:32.870 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:52:32.870 --> 00:52:35.630 align:middle line:84%
And written like a
six-year-old would write.

00:52:35.630 --> 00:52:43.010 align:middle line:84%
But it very clearly says
nurturing, healing, love.

00:52:43.010 --> 00:52:45.380 align:middle line:84%
I feel like that's
a message for me,

00:52:45.380 --> 00:52:48.140 align:middle line:84%
a message for my
family and friends,

00:52:48.140 --> 00:52:50.690 align:middle line:90%
but also for the world.

00:52:50.690 --> 00:52:53.610 align:middle line:84%
Look at how everybody
responded to this tragedy.

00:52:53.610 --> 00:52:57.110 align:middle line:84%
It was in love, an
outpouring of love.

00:52:57.110 --> 00:52:59.270 align:middle line:90%
Sandy Hook chooses love.

00:52:59.270 --> 00:53:02.540 align:middle line:84%
And now I feel like his spirit
is with me all the time.

00:53:02.540 --> 00:53:04.370 align:middle line:90%
I feel him all around.

00:53:04.370 --> 00:53:09.410 align:middle line:84%
And what a blessing it is for
me that I can see those gifts

00:53:09.410 --> 00:53:17.700 align:middle line:84%
and I can accept them, and know
that he served his purpose,

00:53:17.700 --> 00:53:21.530 align:middle line:84%
and he's here and
in heaven and whole.

00:53:21.530 --> 00:53:23.269 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: How did
you meet Scarlett?

00:53:23.269 --> 00:53:24.810 align:middle line:84%
>>NICK: Just through
a mutual friend.

00:53:24.810 --> 00:53:27.494 align:middle line:84%
And actually, Scarlett
had, surprisingly,

00:53:27.494 --> 00:53:29.660 align:middle line:84%
listened to a tapping world
summit a couple of years

00:53:29.660 --> 00:53:30.120 align:middle line:90%
earlier.

00:53:30.120 --> 00:53:30.430 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Oh, wow.

00:53:30.430 --> 00:53:32.013 align:middle line:84%
>>NICK: She was
familiar with tapping.

00:53:32.013 --> 00:53:34.220 align:middle line:84%
And when a friend said Nick
Ortner lives in Newtown,

00:53:34.220 --> 00:53:35.690 align:middle line:90%
she said, oh, my gosh.

00:53:35.690 --> 00:53:38.630 align:middle line:84%
And I was there with Dr.
Leyden just later that night.

00:53:38.630 --> 00:53:40.180 align:middle line:84%
It was like a rainy
Tuesday night,

00:53:40.180 --> 00:53:42.950 align:middle line:84%
and we were just in her home
and actually tapped together

00:53:42.950 --> 00:53:45.710 align:middle line:84%
that night, and have
worked together since.

00:53:45.710 --> 00:53:46.730 align:middle line:10%
>>LISA: Oh, my goodness.

00:53:46.730 --> 00:53:51.230 align:middle line:84%
Now, her son-- and this story
has always impacted me--

00:53:51.230 --> 00:53:54.500 align:middle line:84%
they were rushing or late
or something that morning?

00:53:54.500 --> 00:53:56.570 align:middle line:84%
>>NICK: Yeah, so they
were rushing to school,

00:53:56.570 --> 00:54:01.100 align:middle line:84%
as often happens I'm sure with a
six-year-old, and Jesse wrote--

00:54:01.100 --> 00:54:05.070 align:middle line:84%
it was December 14th, so
it's cold in Connecticut--

00:54:05.070 --> 00:54:07.520 align:middle line:84%
and he wrote in the frost
of the car, I love you

00:54:07.520 --> 00:54:08.807 align:middle line:90%
and it had all these hearts.

00:54:08.807 --> 00:54:11.390 align:middle line:84%
And she said, even though we're
late, I got to get the camera.

00:54:11.390 --> 00:54:12.348 align:middle line:90%
I got to get a picture.

00:54:12.348 --> 00:54:14.390 align:middle line:84%
And that was the last
picture she took of him.

00:54:14.390 --> 00:54:15.190 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Oh my god.

00:54:15.190 --> 00:54:18.650 align:middle line:84%
>>NICK: Right next
to I love you.

00:54:18.650 --> 00:54:19.650 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: I can't imagine.

00:54:19.650 --> 00:54:23.330 align:middle line:84%
And as strong as she
is and the story is--

00:54:23.330 --> 00:54:24.960 align:middle line:90%
you said a story of hope.

00:54:24.960 --> 00:54:25.760 align:middle line:90%
>>NICK: Yeah.

00:54:25.760 --> 00:54:26.760 align:middle line:10%
I know a lot of people--

00:54:26.760 --> 00:54:29.390 align:middle line:10%
I'm so passionate about this
book because-- her book--

00:54:29.390 --> 00:54:31.740 align:middle line:10%
"Nurturing, Healing, Love,"
because it's a story of hope

00:54:31.740 --> 00:54:33.470 align:middle line:10%
and know people
are scared of it.

00:54:33.470 --> 00:54:34.970 align:middle line:84%
Because it's like, I
can't even think about it.

00:54:34.970 --> 00:54:35.720 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Imagine.

00:54:35.720 --> 00:54:36.710 align:middle line:90%
>>NICK: I can't even imagine.

00:54:36.710 --> 00:54:38.376 align:middle line:84%
And I know there's
so much trauma there.

00:54:38.376 --> 00:54:41.360 align:middle line:10%
But when you read the book,
you definitely shed tears.

00:54:41.360 --> 00:54:43.520 align:middle line:10%
